>>NOORY: That's an interesting
analogy about chakras,

00:19:30.880 --> 00:19:31.680 align:middle line:90%
isn't it?

00:19:31.680 --> 00:19:32.160 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yeah.

00:19:32.160 --> 00:19:34.120 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It puts a lot
of things perspective.

00:19:34.120 --> 00:19:34.920 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yeah.

00:19:34.920 --> 00:19:36.960 align:middle line:84%
A lot of people
that come to my work

00:19:36.960 --> 00:19:41.620 align:middle line:84%
come because they have had a
lot of trauma in their lives.

00:19:41.620 --> 00:19:44.790 align:middle line:84%
And it's showing up in their
relationship with money,

00:19:44.790 --> 00:19:47.310 align:middle line:84%
yet they don't know
how to change it.

00:19:47.310 --> 00:19:51.450 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So how would you
weigh, in terms of the scale,

00:19:51.450 --> 00:19:56.940 align:middle line:84%
what you do for people to help
them financial, primarily,

00:19:56.940 --> 00:19:58.530 align:middle line:90%
medical primarily?

00:19:58.530 --> 00:20:00.900 align:middle line:90%
Where does that sit?

00:20:00.900 --> 00:20:03.870 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: I think financial
is the ultimate result

00:20:03.870 --> 00:20:07.000 align:middle line:84%
and the goal that
someone comes thinking,

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:08.940 align:middle line:90%
hey, I need help with my money.

00:20:08.940 --> 00:20:12.000 align:middle line:84%
But when we get into
it, what we find

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:16.950 align:middle line:84%
is that there are these trauma
bubbles that have literally

00:20:16.950 --> 00:20:20.460 align:middle line:84%
stored themselves
in those chakras.

00:20:20.460 --> 00:20:23.880 align:middle line:84%
And those are the things
that are causing them

00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:25.530 align:middle line:90%
the problem with the money.

00:20:25.530 --> 00:20:27.720 align:middle line:84%
But until we look
at those and we

00:20:27.720 --> 00:20:31.710 align:middle line:84%
help them heal those
aspects of the trauma,

00:20:31.710 --> 00:20:33.750 align:middle line:84%
they can't make
the kind of changes

00:20:33.750 --> 00:20:35.070 align:middle line:90%
that they want with the money.

00:20:35.070 --> 00:20:39.870 align:middle line:84%
So I look at it
kind of like I have

00:20:39.870 --> 00:20:42.240 align:middle line:84%
a lot of experience with
money and so it makes

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:43.750 align:middle line:90%
people interested in my work.

00:20:43.750 --> 00:20:45.540 align:middle line:84%
But I also have a
lot of experience

00:20:45.540 --> 00:20:47.820 align:middle line:84%
in looking inside
and figuring out

00:20:47.820 --> 00:20:50.790 align:middle line:84%
how to move through
those traumatic points,

00:20:50.790 --> 00:20:52.680 align:middle line:90%
because I had a lot of them.

00:20:52.680 --> 00:20:55.210 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are you teaching
people how to make more money,

00:20:55.210 --> 00:20:57.913 align:middle line:84%
how to save money, how to
spend money, or all of it?

00:20:57.913 --> 00:20:58.830 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: All of it.

00:20:58.830 --> 00:20:59.630 align:middle line:90%
It's all of it.

00:20:59.630 --> 00:21:01.710 align:middle line:84%
And actually each of
the things you said

00:21:01.710 --> 00:21:05.260 align:middle line:84%
falls into one of the
chakras, which is fascinating.

00:21:05.260 --> 00:21:09.643 align:middle line:84%
So different patterns relate
to different chakras about what

00:21:09.643 --> 00:21:10.560 align:middle line:90%
we're struggling with.

00:21:10.560 --> 00:21:15.090 align:middle line:84%
For example, saving money
or getting into debt

00:21:15.090 --> 00:21:17.190 align:middle line:90%
is in the sacral chakra.

00:21:17.190 --> 00:21:19.770 align:middle line:84%
And so the reason
that is, is that--

00:21:19.770 --> 00:21:21.270 align:middle line:84%
remember how I
said my mom didn't

00:21:21.270 --> 00:21:25.060 align:middle line:84%
feel into her experiences,
she didn't feel things?

00:21:25.060 --> 00:21:26.790 align:middle line:84%
Well, if you think
about debt, debt

00:21:26.790 --> 00:21:29.190 align:middle line:84%
is a classic example
of someone not wanting

00:21:29.190 --> 00:21:32.250 align:middle line:84%
to deal with the present
situation and kind of trying

00:21:32.250 --> 00:21:35.370 align:middle line:84%
to get what they want from
a satisfaction standpoint

00:21:35.370 --> 00:21:39.360 align:middle line:84%
right now but delay into
the future, like avoid.

00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:41.910 align:middle line:84%
And so there's an
avoidance of feeling.

00:21:41.910 --> 00:21:44.610 align:middle line:84%
And I see it over and
over again that people

00:21:44.610 --> 00:21:47.970 align:middle line:84%
who are struggling with debt
or not being able to save money

00:21:47.970 --> 00:21:49.692 align:middle line:90%
have a sacral chakra issue.

00:21:49.692 --> 00:21:51.900 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I was always told,
Leisa, that debt is good.

00:21:51.900 --> 00:21:54.810 align:middle line:84%
There was a movie
where the experts

00:21:54.810 --> 00:21:57.060 align:middle line:90%
said dead tightens a company.

00:21:57.060 --> 00:22:00.570 align:middle line:84%
And there's another
theory of debt

00:22:00.570 --> 00:22:04.320 align:middle line:84%
is basically using other
people's money where you

00:22:04.320 --> 00:22:05.800 align:middle line:90%
don't have a touch your own.

00:22:05.800 --> 00:22:06.940 align:middle line:90%
What do you think of that?

00:22:06.940 --> 00:22:08.900 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: So there's
two things going on.

00:22:08.900 --> 00:22:12.430 align:middle line:84%
One is there's people
who have basically

00:22:12.430 --> 00:22:15.490 align:middle line:84%
been conditioned to believe
that debt is acceptable.

00:22:15.490 --> 00:22:17.950 align:middle line:84%
And it doesn't matter that
you have a lot of debt.

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:22.150 align:middle line:84%
Yet they are kind
of in a lot of pain,

00:22:22.150 --> 00:22:24.940 align:middle line:84%
because they worry about
that debt all the time.

00:22:24.940 --> 00:22:26.830 align:middle line:84%
That's completely
different than when

00:22:26.830 --> 00:22:30.100 align:middle line:84%
you reach a stage
where you're choosing

00:22:30.100 --> 00:22:32.930 align:middle line:84%
to use debt because it helps
you become a better investor,

00:22:32.930 --> 00:22:33.730 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:22:33.730 --> 00:22:36.680 align:middle line:84%
You buy a house with debt
and you create leverage.

00:22:36.680 --> 00:22:37.570 align:middle line:90%
So that helps you.

00:22:37.570 --> 00:22:39.237 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: If you can
support the payment.

00:22:39.237 --> 00:22:40.090 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yes.

00:22:40.090 --> 00:22:43.390 align:middle line:84%
But you have to understand
that's a choice.

00:22:43.390 --> 00:22:46.370 align:middle line:84%
Like if you have a choice,
debt isn't a problem.

00:22:46.370 --> 00:22:49.180 align:middle line:84%
But when you don't have a choice
and you're living in debt,

00:22:49.180 --> 00:22:52.783 align:middle line:84%
and you think that's your whole
life story, that's a problem.

00:22:52.783 --> 00:22:54.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now back to the
chakras for a moment.

00:22:54.700 --> 00:22:57.260 align:middle line:84%
What's happening on the
planet right now with chakras?

00:22:57.260 --> 00:22:59.440 align:middle line:84%
How many people
are aware of these?

00:22:59.440 --> 00:23:01.120 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: Becoming
a lot more--

00:23:01.120 --> 00:23:01.920 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Really?

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:04.090 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: Yeah,
Popular, interesting.

00:23:04.090 --> 00:23:07.340 align:middle line:10%
People are asking a lot
of questions about them.

00:23:07.340 --> 00:23:09.640 align:middle line:10%
I think that people are
curious because they're

00:23:09.640 --> 00:23:12.290 align:middle line:10%
seeing it being written
about and discussed,

00:23:12.290 --> 00:23:13.660 align:middle line:10%
which is exciting.

00:23:13.660 --> 00:23:18.370 align:middle line:84%
The one thing I will say is that
some people look at the chakras

00:23:18.370 --> 00:23:22.130 align:middle line:84%
and they go to somebody to
get them to fix them, right?

00:23:22.130 --> 00:23:25.730 align:middle line:84%
So I go to somebody and they
balance my chakras for me.

00:23:25.730 --> 00:23:27.530 align:middle line:90%
I'm not a big fan of that.

00:23:27.530 --> 00:23:31.120 align:middle line:84%
I actually feel like
it's like if you

00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:33.185 align:middle line:84%
can learn how to
do it for yourself,

00:23:33.185 --> 00:23:35.060 align:middle line:84%
you're going to be in
a much better position.

00:23:35.060 --> 00:23:40.120 align:middle line:84%
So learning how to actually
manage, and look inside,

00:23:40.120 --> 00:23:43.090 align:middle line:84%
and tune up your
chakras on your own

00:23:43.090 --> 00:23:45.760 align:middle line:84%
is going to be way more
empowering than going

00:23:45.760 --> 00:23:47.300 align:middle line:84%
to somebody and
saying you fix me.

00:23:47.300 --> 00:23:48.250 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:23:48.250 --> 00:23:52.390 align:middle line:84%
Are there ways for these
people to do this naturally

00:23:52.390 --> 00:23:54.730 align:middle line:84%
where they're not schooled,
they're not trained,

00:23:54.730 --> 00:23:56.170 align:middle line:90%
it just happens?

00:23:56.170 --> 00:23:57.380 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: I think so.

00:23:57.380 --> 00:24:00.250 align:middle line:84%
I think a lot of people
are doing this already.

00:24:00.250 --> 00:24:02.980 align:middle line:84%
Maybe there's a certain
area in their body

00:24:02.980 --> 00:24:05.200 align:middle line:84%
that they pay a lot
of attention to.

00:24:05.200 --> 00:24:07.790 align:middle line:84%
I practiced Buddhism
for many years.

00:24:07.790 --> 00:24:09.760 align:middle line:84%
And one of the meditations
that we would do

00:24:09.760 --> 00:24:11.620 align:middle line:90%
would be taking and giving.

00:24:11.620 --> 00:24:15.040 align:middle line:84%
And that's a very heart
chakra centered practice.

00:24:15.040 --> 00:24:17.170 align:middle line:84%
So you wouldn't
realize necessarily

00:24:17.170 --> 00:24:18.940 align:middle line:84%
that you were working
on your heart chakra

00:24:18.940 --> 00:24:20.530 align:middle line:84%
when you did taking
and giving, which

00:24:20.530 --> 00:24:23.980 align:middle line:84%
is like breathing in suffering
and breathing out healing.

00:24:23.980 --> 00:24:26.420 align:middle line:84%
Or there's a lot of
different ways to do it.

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:28.870 align:middle line:84%
But you're doing it
without much training.

00:24:28.870 --> 00:24:31.150 align:middle line:84%
So the difference
is is that when

00:24:31.150 --> 00:24:34.510 align:middle line:84%
you start to realize that there
are these messages that really

00:24:34.510 --> 00:24:36.790 align:middle line:84%
tell you the whole
story of your life

00:24:36.790 --> 00:24:38.800 align:middle line:84%
that are captured
in the chakras,

00:24:38.800 --> 00:24:40.300 align:middle line:84%
I think you start
realizing that you

00:24:40.300 --> 00:24:42.070 align:middle line:84%
could be working on
many different levels

00:24:42.070 --> 00:24:43.270 align:middle line:90%
at the same time.

00:24:43.270 --> 00:24:45.730 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How come some people
can do it naturally and other

00:24:45.730 --> 00:24:46.915 align:middle line:90%
people can't?

00:24:46.915 --> 00:24:48.240 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Ah, great question.

00:24:48.240 --> 00:24:49.740 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All my
questions are great.

00:24:49.740 --> 00:24:53.320 align:middle line:90%
We've got a great staff here.

00:24:53.320 --> 00:24:55.270 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: So I
think it has a lot

00:24:55.270 --> 00:24:57.385 align:middle line:90%
to do with mindfulness for some.

00:24:57.385 --> 00:25:02.110 align:middle line:84%
For me I came to this from
meditation and looking within.

00:25:02.110 --> 00:25:04.750 align:middle line:84%
But I've met plenty of people
from their earliest memories

00:25:04.750 --> 00:25:06.850 align:middle line:84%
in life, they came
in and they were

00:25:06.850 --> 00:25:10.970 align:middle line:84%
deeply tuned in to what was
going on inside of them.

00:25:10.970 --> 00:25:12.550 align:middle line:90%
And it was just natural.

00:25:12.550 --> 00:25:14.590 align:middle line:84%
They didn't receive
any training for it.

00:25:14.590 --> 00:25:17.493 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And little children,
do they have this ability, too?

00:25:17.493 --> 00:25:19.660 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: Yeah, I think
that we do this naturally.

00:25:19.660 --> 00:25:21.160 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Some more than others?

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:22.640 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yes, definitely.

00:25:22.640 --> 00:25:27.220 align:middle line:84%
I remember when I was a child
I would go into what now I

00:25:27.220 --> 00:25:30.100 align:middle line:84%
see is what's called
Samadhi I would

00:25:30.100 --> 00:25:34.570 align:middle line:84%
go into super deep
meditation practices.

00:25:34.570 --> 00:25:37.450 align:middle line:84%
When I had done something
wrong and I was in trouble,

00:25:37.450 --> 00:25:39.620 align:middle line:90%
I would go into a ball.

00:25:39.620 --> 00:25:42.350 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't recognize
what I was doing,

00:25:42.350 --> 00:25:43.933 align:middle line:84%
it was just a
natural part of me.

00:25:43.933 --> 00:25:44.850 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Did you pout?

00:25:44.850 --> 00:25:48.070 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: I think it was
like a form of escapism,

00:25:48.070 --> 00:25:50.850 align:middle line:84%
like I was upset at my family
for putting me in the corner.

00:25:50.850 --> 00:25:53.380 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Nobody can see you
in this little ball, right?

00:25:53.380 --> 00:25:54.180 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Right.

00:25:54.180 --> 00:25:56.620 align:middle line:84%
But then later in life
when I started meditating

00:25:56.620 --> 00:26:01.390 align:middle line:84%
and I'd reach these really
deep stages of just seeing

00:26:01.390 --> 00:26:04.180 align:middle line:84%
everything, in
that moment I could

00:26:04.180 --> 00:26:07.390 align:middle line:84%
see that it was the exact same
situation of what I would go

00:26:07.390 --> 00:26:09.490 align:middle line:90%
into when I was a little kid.

00:26:09.490 --> 00:26:12.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You have looked at
the power of forgiveness.

00:26:12.940 --> 00:26:14.650 align:middle line:90%
What is so important about that?

00:26:14.650 --> 00:26:17.440 align:middle line:84%
Because there are some
things I can forgive,

00:26:17.440 --> 00:26:19.660 align:middle line:90%
there are other things I cannot.

00:26:19.660 --> 00:26:23.390 align:middle line:84%
If somebody physically
harmed a member of my family,

00:26:23.390 --> 00:26:24.940 align:middle line:90%
I can't forgive that.

00:26:24.940 --> 00:26:28.690 align:middle line:84%
Now I could forgive someone
who is drunk, and gets

00:26:28.690 --> 00:26:32.360 align:middle line:84%
into a tragic accident, and
hurt somebody in my family.

00:26:32.360 --> 00:26:34.990 align:middle line:84%
I can forgive that,
because that's a sickness.

00:26:34.990 --> 00:26:36.430 align:middle line:90%
That's a mistake.

00:26:36.430 --> 00:26:39.490 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't I'm out
to hurt somebody.

00:26:39.490 --> 00:26:42.880 align:middle line:84%
But somebody who would blatantly
murder someone or harm someone,

00:26:42.880 --> 00:26:43.850 align:middle line:90%
I can't forgive that.

00:26:43.850 --> 00:26:45.730 align:middle line:84%
Now is that something
wrong with me?

00:26:45.730 --> 00:26:47.640 align:middle line:90%
Should I forgive that?

00:26:47.640 --> 00:26:49.390 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: I don't
think that "should" is

00:26:49.390 --> 00:26:51.610 align:middle line:90%
the right word for anything.

00:26:51.610 --> 00:26:54.730 align:middle line:84%
But I will say that
in my own journey,

00:26:54.730 --> 00:26:56.950 align:middle line:90%
my father was brutally murdered.

00:26:56.950 --> 00:27:00.580 align:middle line:84%
And his ex-girlfriend
and her boyfriend

00:27:00.580 --> 00:27:02.710 align:middle line:90%
had conspired to buy a gun.

00:27:02.710 --> 00:27:03.970 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Oh my god.

00:27:03.970 --> 00:27:04.770 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yeah.

00:27:04.770 --> 00:27:08.400 align:middle line:84%
And it wasn't right
away, but after

00:27:08.400 --> 00:27:11.850 align:middle line:84%
years of exploring
forgiveness practice,

00:27:11.850 --> 00:27:16.830 align:middle line:84%
I came to the
realization that until I

00:27:16.830 --> 00:27:21.330 align:middle line:84%
reached a place of forgiveness
where I could have compassion

00:27:21.330 --> 00:27:22.960 align:middle line:90%
for them doing what they did--

00:27:22.960 --> 00:27:23.760 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Why?

00:27:23.760 --> 00:27:25.745 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: --I wasn't free.

00:27:25.745 --> 00:27:27.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And so you're
telling me you forgave them?

00:27:27.870 --> 00:27:28.670 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yes.

00:27:28.670 --> 00:27:29.970 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Why?

00:27:29.970 --> 00:27:32.880 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: Because I
was holding on to hatred.

00:27:32.880 --> 00:27:35.040 align:middle line:84%
And there was no
space inside of me

00:27:35.040 --> 00:27:37.500 align:middle line:84%
to hold on to the
hatred for them.

00:27:37.500 --> 00:27:41.100 align:middle line:84%
As I looked at my
own hatred, all I saw

00:27:41.100 --> 00:27:44.070 align:middle line:84%
was more pain and
suffering for myself.

00:27:44.070 --> 00:27:46.480 align:middle line:90%
And it's like it set me free.

00:27:46.480 --> 00:27:47.280 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:48.150 align:middle line:90%
That's the classic idea.

00:27:48.150 --> 00:27:50.108 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But doesn't that
give them the feeling

00:27:50.108 --> 00:27:52.420 align:middle line:90%
as if it was OK?

00:27:52.420 --> 00:27:53.220 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: No.

00:27:53.220 --> 00:27:55.725 align:middle line:84%
Because I think there's a
big difference between--

00:27:55.725 --> 00:27:56.565 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did they
go to jail for this?

00:27:56.565 --> 00:27:57.440 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: They did.

00:27:57.440 --> 00:28:01.140 align:middle line:84%
They both went to jail,
very short sentences,

00:28:01.140 --> 00:28:03.510 align:middle line:90%
also kind of shocking.

00:28:03.510 --> 00:28:07.110 align:middle line:84%
But what happened
was it's not that I'm

00:28:07.110 --> 00:28:09.490 align:middle line:90%
condoning their behavior.

00:28:09.490 --> 00:28:11.590 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
where maybe the snag is.

00:28:11.590 --> 00:28:12.840 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Of course you're not.

00:28:12.840 --> 00:28:15.490 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: No, no, it's
not that way at all.

00:28:15.490 --> 00:28:19.050 align:middle line:84%
But what I did do in my own
practice-- and each of us

00:28:19.050 --> 00:28:20.230 align:middle line:90%
have to go through this.

00:28:20.230 --> 00:28:22.313 align:middle line:84%
This is why you could never
tell somebody you just

00:28:22.313 --> 00:28:23.340 align:middle line:90%
need to forgive someone.

00:28:23.340 --> 00:28:26.400 align:middle line:84%
I think we have to go
inside of the experience.

00:28:26.400 --> 00:28:29.910 align:middle line:84%
And I'll add a little
feature to what was going on.

00:28:29.910 --> 00:28:34.020 align:middle line:84%
My father was estranged from
our family when he was killed.

00:28:34.020 --> 00:28:36.750 align:middle line:90%
And he had done a lot of things.

00:28:36.750 --> 00:28:38.820 align:middle line:90%
He was a lifelong drug user.

00:28:38.820 --> 00:28:41.025 align:middle line:90%
And he was very manipulative.

00:28:41.025 --> 00:28:42.530 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So he was
going downhill.

00:28:42.530 --> 00:28:43.330 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yeah.

00:28:43.330 --> 00:28:46.980 align:middle line:84%
And when he was
killed, and I started

00:28:46.980 --> 00:28:49.560 align:middle line:84%
trying to look at
what had happened,

00:28:49.560 --> 00:28:52.410 align:middle line:84%
I started to notice that there
had been these letters that

00:28:52.410 --> 00:28:54.900 align:middle line:84%
went back and forth between
him and the people who

00:28:54.900 --> 00:28:56.010 align:middle line:90%
had killed him.

00:28:56.010 --> 00:28:58.020 align:middle line:90%
And there was a story behind it.

00:28:58.020 --> 00:29:02.040 align:middle line:84%
Now it doesn't justify
or anything like that,

00:29:02.040 --> 00:29:07.350 align:middle line:84%
but I could see that my father's
behavior had most likely caused

00:29:07.350 --> 00:29:10.920 align:middle line:84%
them to be very
afraid for their life.

00:29:10.920 --> 00:29:14.010 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Was that their
motivation, self defense?

00:29:14.010 --> 00:29:15.066 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Kind of.

00:29:15.066 --> 00:29:17.358 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: There wasn't some
insurance scam involved here

00:29:17.358 --> 00:29:17.670 align:middle line:90%
or anything like that?

00:29:17.670 --> 00:29:18.900 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: No, nothing.

00:29:18.900 --> 00:29:19.700 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:29:19.700 --> 00:29:27.030 align:middle line:84%
But what I saw was that in the
end where it all came together

00:29:27.030 --> 00:29:31.950 align:middle line:84%
is that every single
person, even though it looks

00:29:31.950 --> 00:29:33.703 align:middle line:90%
different from the outside--

00:29:33.703 --> 00:29:35.370 align:middle line:84%
first of all, it
always looks different.

00:29:35.370 --> 00:29:40.620 align:middle line:84%
But when you go deep inside
of the human experience, what

00:29:40.620 --> 00:29:45.450 align:middle line:84%
we find is that everyone is
doing the best that they can.

00:29:45.450 --> 00:29:47.070 align:middle line:84%
And that there
have been a series

00:29:47.070 --> 00:29:49.110 align:middle line:90%
of events that have occurred--

00:29:49.110 --> 00:29:52.290 align:middle line:84%
whether it be sexual
trauma at a very young age

00:29:52.290 --> 00:29:55.332 align:middle line:84%
for someone, abuse,
or many things

00:29:55.332 --> 00:29:56.790 align:middle line:84%
that could have
happened to someone

00:29:56.790 --> 00:30:01.140 align:middle line:84%
that we don't have any
idea the story behind it.

00:30:01.140 --> 00:30:02.880 align:middle line:90%
And then they do an action.

00:30:02.880 --> 00:30:05.200 align:middle line:84%
And we say you're
a horrible person.

00:30:05.200 --> 00:30:07.980 align:middle line:84%
But we don't know
all of the reasons

00:30:07.980 --> 00:30:11.170 align:middle line:84%
why they do what they
do in that moment.

00:30:11.170 --> 00:30:13.800 align:middle line:84%
And when I could
see that for myself,

00:30:13.800 --> 00:30:15.960 align:middle line:84%
I could see it for
my father's killers.

00:30:15.960 --> 00:30:18.570 align:middle line:84%
I could see it for other
people that I would easily

00:30:18.570 --> 00:30:21.720 align:middle line:84%
say they're bad people,
and I just don't like them.

00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:24.510 align:middle line:84%
But after a while of
questioning this way

00:30:24.510 --> 00:30:28.290 align:middle line:84%
of just saying, I can't
forgive and looking inside

00:30:28.290 --> 00:30:31.380 align:middle line:90%
and saying, if I make mistakes--

00:30:31.380 --> 00:30:33.510 align:middle line:84%
I mean, granted not
that kind of mistake--

00:30:33.510 --> 00:30:36.060 align:middle line:84%
but if I make mistakes
and I can't forgive myself

00:30:36.060 --> 00:30:38.460 align:middle line:84%
for those mistakes,
then I definitely

00:30:38.460 --> 00:30:39.880 align:middle line:90%
can't forgive other people.

00:30:39.880 --> 00:30:42.090 align:middle line:84%
So I started learning
how to forgive myself

00:30:42.090 --> 00:30:44.280 align:middle line:84%
for all kinds of
stuff that I've done.

00:30:44.280 --> 00:30:45.780 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I want you
to see a portion

00:30:45.780 --> 00:30:47.880 align:middle line:84%
of "Open Minds with
Regina Meredith"

00:30:47.880 --> 00:30:51.000 align:middle line:84%
where she talked with Dr.
James Hardt about the science

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:52.380 align:middle line:90%
behind forgiveness.

00:30:52.380 --> 00:30:53.730 align:middle line:90%
Let's see if you agree with him.

00:30:53.730 --> 00:30:54.370 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:30:54.370 --> 00:30:57.090 align:middle line:10%
- Can you talk a little bit more
about the forgiveness process?

00:30:57.090 --> 00:30:59.370 align:middle line:10%
- Sure.

00:30:59.370 --> 00:31:01.740 align:middle line:90%
Give you a little background.

00:31:01.740 --> 00:31:05.460 align:middle line:84%
Everybody in America has
heard of the Gallup Poll.

00:31:05.460 --> 00:31:09.150 align:middle line:84%
For a long time before the death
of Sir John Templeton, a very

00:31:09.150 --> 00:31:12.960 align:middle line:84%
spiritual man and a good friend
of George Gallup, every couple

00:31:12.960 --> 00:31:15.510 align:middle line:84%
of years Sir John
would get George

00:31:15.510 --> 00:31:17.640 align:middle line:90%
to do a poll on forgiveness.

00:31:17.640 --> 00:31:21.090 align:middle line:84%
Well one time I had a chance
to read one of the details.

00:31:21.090 --> 00:31:23.640 align:middle line:84%
And in rating the
importance of forgiveness

00:31:23.640 --> 00:31:26.040 align:middle line:84%
from zero, not at
all, up to four,

00:31:26.040 --> 00:31:29.970 align:middle line:84%
extremely, 80% of Americans
said they considered forgiveness

00:31:29.970 --> 00:31:34.170 align:middle line:84%
extremely important,
80% then of those

00:31:34.170 --> 00:31:36.900 align:middle line:84%
who considered it extremely
important, George Gallup asked,

00:31:36.900 --> 00:31:38.400 align:middle line:90%
well, can you do it?

00:31:38.400 --> 00:31:41.010 align:middle line:90%
85% said no.

00:31:41.010 --> 00:31:45.690 align:middle line:84%
Even God's help was not
effective in producing

00:31:45.690 --> 00:31:48.090 align:middle line:84%
what we call effective
forgiveness for most people.

00:31:48.090 --> 00:31:50.460 align:middle line:90%
85% said they could not do it.

00:31:50.460 --> 00:31:52.470 align:middle line:10%
Of the things that
Gallup asked about,

00:31:52.470 --> 00:31:54.600 align:middle line:10%
there was only one thing
that was correlated

00:31:54.600 --> 00:31:55.740 align:middle line:10%
with effective forgiveness.

00:31:55.740 --> 00:31:58.590 align:middle line:90%
And that was meditative prayer.

00:31:58.590 --> 00:32:00.900 align:middle line:84%
Well when you take
meditative as an adverb

00:32:00.900 --> 00:32:03.750 align:middle line:84%
and put it in front of a
verb, like meditative fishing,

00:32:03.750 --> 00:32:06.940 align:middle line:84%
meditative gardening, meditative
sewing, meditative reading,

00:32:06.940 --> 00:32:09.160 align:middle line:90%
what I see are more alpha waves.

00:32:09.160 --> 00:32:11.830 align:middle line:84%
And so in a sense,
George Gallup has

00:32:11.830 --> 00:32:14.720 align:middle line:84%
revealed that effective
forgiveness requires

00:32:14.720 --> 00:32:15.520 align:middle line:90%
more alpha waves.

00:32:15.520 --> 00:32:16.345 align:middle line:90%
[END PLAYBACK]

00:32:16.345 --> 00:32:18.220 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So what do you
think of that, Leisa?

00:32:18.220 --> 00:32:20.570 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: I love it.

00:32:20.570 --> 00:32:22.280 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I want you
to give me a test.

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:23.080 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yeah?

00:32:23.080 --> 00:32:25.180 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Give me a
test on forgiveness.

00:32:25.180 --> 00:32:28.090 align:middle line:84%
Throw things my way
and ask me if I would

00:32:28.090 --> 00:32:30.735 align:middle line:90%
forgive that special thing.

00:32:30.735 --> 00:32:31.535 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: OK.

00:32:31.535 --> 00:32:34.150 align:middle line:90%


00:32:34.150 --> 00:32:35.600 align:middle line:90%
Are you married?

00:32:35.600 --> 00:32:37.030 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Maybe.

00:32:37.030 --> 00:32:38.800 align:middle line:84%
I never discuss
my personal life.

00:32:38.800 --> 00:32:39.850 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: OK.

00:32:39.850 --> 00:32:43.270 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just supposed to-- so
if your wife cheated on you,

00:32:43.270 --> 00:32:45.070 align:middle line:90%
would you forgive her?

00:32:45.070 --> 00:32:46.433 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes.

00:32:46.433 --> 00:32:48.100 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: Would you
forgive the person

00:32:48.100 --> 00:32:50.320 align:middle line:90%
who she was also with?

00:32:50.320 --> 00:32:52.390 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes.

00:32:52.390 --> 00:32:53.190 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: OK.

00:32:53.190 --> 00:32:54.260 align:middle line:90%
That was a hard one.

00:32:54.260 --> 00:32:57.720 align:middle line:90%
So you already did a hard one.

00:32:57.720 --> 00:32:58.860 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: If I were married.

00:32:58.860 --> 00:33:01.140 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: OK.

00:33:01.140 --> 00:33:04.530 align:middle line:84%
If a drunk driver
killed a child.

00:33:04.530 --> 00:33:05.700 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes.

00:33:05.700 --> 00:33:08.440 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yes.

00:33:08.440 --> 00:33:11.290 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now I want
to qualify this.

00:33:11.290 --> 00:33:12.168 align:middle line:90%
It's not easy.

00:33:12.168 --> 00:33:13.210 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: I understand.

00:33:13.210 --> 00:33:14.010 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: OK?

00:33:14.010 --> 00:33:17.320 align:middle line:84%
But based on those scenarios
you've just mentioned, yes.

00:33:17.320 --> 00:33:18.620 align:middle line:90%
Throw a few more my way.

00:33:18.620 --> 00:33:23.790 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: If a financial
advisor stole all your money.

00:33:23.790 --> 00:33:25.530 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I probably
would eventually

00:33:25.530 --> 00:33:27.090 align:middle line:90%
forgive somebody for that.

00:33:27.090 --> 00:33:29.760 align:middle line:84%
I'd want to find out
why he did what he did.

00:33:29.760 --> 00:33:32.130 align:middle line:90%
Was he in some financial mess?

00:33:32.130 --> 00:33:34.980 align:middle line:90%
Was he in trouble, you know?

00:33:34.980 --> 00:33:36.120 align:middle line:90%
Something like that.

00:33:36.120 --> 00:33:37.260 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yeah.

00:33:37.260 --> 00:33:41.070 align:middle line:84%
A good friend lied to you
about something important.

00:33:41.070 --> 00:33:44.170 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I'd be disappointed,
but I'd forgive them.

00:33:44.170 --> 00:33:45.835 align:middle line:84%
So there's a lot of
things I'd forgive.

00:33:45.835 --> 00:33:46.635 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yeah.

00:33:46.635 --> 00:33:49.200 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You haven't asked
me about the murderer.

00:33:49.200 --> 00:33:53.160 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: So the
murderer in the case of I

00:33:53.160 --> 00:33:54.740 align:middle line:90%
mean what happened in my family.

00:33:54.740 --> 00:33:57.720 align:middle line:84%
So if someone
murdered your parent?

00:33:57.720 --> 00:34:02.470 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It depends, I guess,
on the motive behind it.

00:34:02.470 --> 00:34:04.680 align:middle line:84%
Just based on that
question, no, I

00:34:04.680 --> 00:34:06.120 align:middle line:90%
would not forgive them for that.

00:34:06.120 --> 00:34:09.360 align:middle line:84%
I'd want them to fry in
hell for what they did.

00:34:09.360 --> 00:34:12.210 align:middle line:84%
I'd want them to get the
electric chair for what

00:34:12.210 --> 00:34:14.400 align:middle line:90%
they did.

00:34:14.400 --> 00:34:16.860 align:middle line:90%
But we don't know, for example--

00:34:16.860 --> 00:34:19.630 align:middle line:84%
and don't take this
the wrong way--

00:34:19.630 --> 00:34:22.750 align:middle line:84%
if your father was
doing things to them and

00:34:22.750 --> 00:34:26.386 align:middle line:84%
they saw this as
self-protection.

00:34:26.386 --> 00:34:27.219 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Totally.

00:34:27.219 --> 00:34:28.210 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: We don't know that.

00:34:28.210 --> 00:34:28.670 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yes.

00:34:28.670 --> 00:34:30.128 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And that
could be a reason

00:34:30.128 --> 00:34:32.350 align:middle line:84%
why they didn't get
a lot of sentencing

00:34:32.350 --> 00:34:33.550 align:middle line:90%
when they got convicted.

00:34:33.550 --> 00:34:34.350 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yes.

00:34:34.350 --> 00:34:37.610 align:middle line:84%
I'm most sure that
that's the case.

00:34:37.610 --> 00:34:39.690 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: But I would forgive--

00:34:39.690 --> 00:34:42.239 align:middle line:84%
unlike the 85% who
said they could not

00:34:42.239 --> 00:34:45.090 align:middle line:90%
forgive in that study--

00:34:45.090 --> 00:34:49.960 align:middle line:84%
I would forgive most
episodes in time,

00:34:49.960 --> 00:34:52.690 align:middle line:84%
maybe not immediately,
but in time,

00:34:52.690 --> 00:34:57.880 align:middle line:84%
other than the clear cut
guy who broke into a house

00:34:57.880 --> 00:35:00.160 align:middle line:84%
and murdered your family
or something like that

00:35:00.160 --> 00:35:01.810 align:middle line:90%
in cold blood.

00:35:01.810 --> 00:35:04.130 align:middle line:90%
I couldn't forgive that.

00:35:04.130 --> 00:35:05.390 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yeah.

00:35:05.390 --> 00:35:09.320 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Truman Capote, when
he wrote the book "Cold Blood,"

00:35:09.320 --> 00:35:15.260 align:middle line:84%
talked with the two murderers
who broke into that house

00:35:15.260 --> 00:35:18.410 align:middle line:84%
and killed the family
for several years

00:35:18.410 --> 00:35:21.860 align:middle line:84%
before he wrote the book as
he was doing his research.

00:35:21.860 --> 00:35:23.810 align:middle line:90%
He began to like them.

00:35:23.810 --> 00:35:26.120 align:middle line:90%
He began to understand them.

00:35:26.120 --> 00:35:29.070 align:middle line:84%
And to me there's
no excuse for that.

00:35:29.070 --> 00:35:30.970 align:middle line:90%
None.

00:35:30.970 --> 00:35:32.645 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: No excuse
for what they did.

00:35:32.645 --> 00:35:33.445 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:35:33.445 --> 00:35:34.403 align:middle line:90%
You can't forgive them.

00:35:34.403 --> 00:35:36.820 align:middle line:90%
But some people can.

00:35:36.820 --> 00:35:38.370 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yeah.

00:35:38.370 --> 00:35:40.620 align:middle line:84%
You know I like the
video where he said

00:35:40.620 --> 00:35:43.110 align:middle line:90%
"the meditative forgiveness."

00:35:43.110 --> 00:35:46.080 align:middle line:90%
This idea that we look within.

00:35:46.080 --> 00:35:47.910 align:middle line:90%
We ask the questions.

00:35:47.910 --> 00:35:52.860 align:middle line:84%
I think that most of the
time it's like nobody's

00:35:52.860 --> 00:35:56.640 align:middle line:84%
going to fault me for not
forgiving the people who

00:35:56.640 --> 00:35:57.600 align:middle line:90%
killed my father.

00:35:57.600 --> 00:35:58.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's an
individual thing.

00:35:58.770 --> 00:35:59.190 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Yes.

00:35:59.190 --> 00:35:59.700 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's you.

00:35:59.700 --> 00:36:00.570 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: It's me.

00:36:00.570 --> 00:36:04.500 align:middle line:84%
It was me realizing that
that wasn't serving me

00:36:04.500 --> 00:36:08.610 align:middle line:84%
and that I didn't want to
live in hatred and anger.

00:36:08.610 --> 00:36:12.060 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Does forgiveness
give you closure?

00:36:12.060 --> 00:36:13.650 align:middle line:90%
>>PETERSON: Very much so.

00:36:13.650 --> 00:36:16.200 align:middle line:84%
I don't think I
could have closed

00:36:16.200 --> 00:36:19.020 align:middle line:84%
the door on that
chapter of my life

00:36:19.020 --> 00:36:21.810 align:middle line:84%
and feel like I could talk
about it here like we're

00:36:21.810 --> 00:36:23.903 align:middle line:84%
talking about it had
I not done that work.

00:36:23.903 --> 00:36:25.320 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Could you
forgive a woman

00:36:25.320 --> 00:36:28.380 align:middle line:84%
who stole a child
from another family,

00:36:28.380 --> 00:36:32.540 align:middle line:84%
kidnapped them, and raised
them, loved the child,

00:36:32.540 --> 00:36:34.805 align:middle line:90%
but literally stole the kid?

00:36:34.805 --> 00:36:36.470 align:middle line:90%
Could you forgive that person?

00:36:36.470 --> 00:36:41.000 align:middle line:84%
>>PETERSON: Just like you, it
would take me a lot of time.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:44.100 align:middle line:84%
Like it is not an
instant thing for me.

00:36:44.100 --> 00:36:45.560 align:middle line:90%
I would look inside of it.

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:47.810 align:middle line:84%
I'd want to know
more if I could.

00:36:47.810 --> 00:36:50.660 align:middle line:84%
If I couldn't I
would try to find--

00:36:50.660 --> 00:36:54.410 align:middle line:84%
knowing that someone who
had made a bad decision

00:36:54.410 --> 00:36:58.100 align:middle line:84%
but then lived in love and
cherished these children

00:36:58.100 --> 00:37:01.130 align:middle line:84%
as if they were
her own, that would

00:37:01.130 --> 00:37:05.030 align:middle line:84%
help me to find some
place inside of myself

00:37:05.030 --> 00:37:07.850 align:middle line:84%
that I could be
at peace with it.

00:37:07.850 --> 00:37:14.240 align:middle line:84%
But again I think that it's
like more than anything,

00:37:14.240 --> 00:37:18.740 align:middle line:84%
we live our lives oftentimes
in great suffering

00:37:18.740 --> 00:37:21.530 align:middle line:84%
